'''James Barry ''' (born 29 June 1990) is an Irish [[hurling|hurler]] who plays for [[Tipperary Senior Hurling Championship|Tipperary Senior Championship]] club [[Upperchurch-Drombane GAA|Upperchurch-Drombane]] and at inter-county level with the [[Tipperary senior hurling team]]. He usually lines out as a full-back.<ref>{{citeweb|url = http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-games/hurling/happy-as-barry-in-new-accidental-fullback-job-30566161.html|title= Happy as Barry in new 'accidental' full-back job|date=6 September 2014|work=Irish Independent|accessdate=9 September 2014}}</ref>	

==Playing career==
===Thurles CBS===

Barry first came to prominence as a hurler with Thurles CBS. He played in every grade before eventually joining the college's senior team. On 8 March 2008, he lined out at centre-back when Thurles CBS suffered a 1-11 to 0-07 defeat by [[De La Salle College Waterford|De La Salle College]] from [[Waterford]] in the [[Dr. Harty Cup|Harty Cup final]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/sport/hurling/mcgrath-puts-harty-joy-down-to-team-spirit-26429159.html|title=McGrath puts Harty joy down to team spirit|publisher=Irish Independent|date=10 March 2008|accessdate=14 February 2019|first=|last=}}</ref> Barry was again at centre-back when Thurles CBS and De La Salle renewed their rivalry in the [[Dr. Croke Cup|All-Ireland final]]. The game ended in a 1-15 to 2-12 draw.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:_8etMXiIH38J:https://www.irishtimes.com/sport/croke-cup-remains-to-be-claimed-1.912976+&cd=2&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=ie|title=Croke Cup remains to be claimed|date=14 April 2008|publisher=Irish Times|accessdate=2 January 2019|first=|last=}}</ref> The replay a week later saw Barry end up on the losing side following a 2-09 to 2-08 victory for De La Salle College.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/sport/gaa/match-reports/de-la-salle-hold-their-nerve-60765.html|title=De La Salle hold their nerve|date=21 April 2008|publisher=Irish Examiner|accessdate=2 January 2019|first=|last=}}</ref>

On 7 March 2009, Barry captained Thurles CBS to a second successive appearance in the Harty Cup final. A 3-15 to 0-10 defeat of St. Caimin's Community School from [[Shannon, County Clare|Shannon]] saw him claim a winners' medal. An injury resulted in Barry being named on the bench for the All-Ireland final against [[St Augustine's and Good Counsel College, New Ross|Good Counsel College]] from [[New Ross]] on 13 April 2009. He came on as a half-time substitute and collected a winners' medal following the 1-17 to 1-15 victory.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:z0inZqDnSL8J:https://www.irishtimes.com/sport/thurles-end-their-long-wait-1.744653+&cd=1&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=ie|title=Thurles end their long wait|date=14 April 2009|publisher=Irish Times|accessdate=2 January 2019|first=|last=}}</ref>

===University College Cork===

Barry studied at [[University College Cork]] and joined the [[UCC GAA|senior hurling team]] in his second year at the university. On 3 March 2012, he was at right wing-back when UCC defeated the [[CIT GAA|Cork Institute of Technology]] by 2-15 to 2-14 to win the [[Fitzgibbon Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/archives/2012/0305/ireland/corry-seals-deal-for-ucc-in-thrilling-centenary-final-186050.html|title=Corry seals deal for UCC in thrilling centenary final|publisher=Irish Examiner|date=5 March 2012|accessdate=19 August 2013|first=Fintan|last=O'Toole}}</ref>

On 2 March 2013, Barry lined out at right wing-back in a second consecutive Fitzgibbon Cup final. He ended the game with a second winners' medal following UCC's 2-17 to 2-12 defeat of [[Mary Immaculate College]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/archives/2013/0304/ireland/ucc-do-it-for-oaposconnor-224443.html|title=UCC do it for O’Connor|publisher=Irish Examiner|date=4 March 2013|accessdate=19 August 2013|first=Diarmuid|last=O'Flynn}}</ref>

===Upperchurch-Drombane===

Barry joined the [[Upperchurch-Drombane GAA|Upperchurch-Drombane]] club at a young age and played in all grades at juvenile and underage levels, enjoying championship success in the under-21 grade. He was just 15-years-old when he first became involved in Upperchurch-Drombane's top adult team.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gaa.ie/features/feature/club-james-barry-upperchurch-drombane/|title=My Club: James Barry - Upperchurch-Drombane|publisher=GAA website|date=1 September 2016|accessdate=18 June 2019|first=John|last=Harrington}}</ref>

===Tipperary===
====Minor and under-21====

Barry was just 16-years-old when he was selected for the [[Tipperary GAA|Tipperary]] minor hurling team prior to the start of the [[2007 All-Ireland Minor Hurling Championship#Munster Minor Hurling Championship|2007 Munster Championship]]. He made his first appearance for the team on 2 May 2007 when he came on as a 26th-minute substitute for [[Joe Gallagher (hurler)|Joe Gallagher]] at midfield in a 3-12 to 1-11 defeat of [[Clare GAA|Clare]]. Barry was again named on the bench when Tipperary faced [[Cork GAA|Cork]] in the  [[Munster Minor Hurling Championship|Munster final]] on 8 July 2007. He was again introduced as a substitute and ended the game with a winners' medal following the 0-18 to 1-11 victory. On 2 September 2007, Barry was selected at right wing-back when Tipperary faced Cork in the [[2007 All-Ireland Minor Hurling Championship#All-Ireland Minor Hurling Championship|All-Ireland final]]. He ended the game with an [[All-Ireland Minor Hurling Championship|All-Ireland]] medal following the 3-14 to 2-11 victory.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.independent.ie/sport/hurling/carey-fires-tipperary-to-double-minor-glory-26315499.html|title=Carey fires Tipperary to double minor glory|date=3 September 2007|publisher=Irish Independent|accessdate=12 June 2019|first=|last=}}</ref>

Barry was again eligible for the Tipperary minor team in [[2008 All-Ireland Minor Hurling Championship#Munster Minor Hurling Championship|2008]]. He lined out at right wing-back when Tipperary suffered a 0-19 to 0-18 defeat by Cork in the Munster final on 13 July 2008.

On 14 July 2010, Barry made his first appearance for the Tipperary under-21 team. He lined out at right wing-back when Tipperary defeated Cork by 2-17 to 0-21. Barry was again at right wing-back when Tipperary faced [[Clare GAA|Clare]] in the [[2010 All-Ireland Under-21 Hurling Championship#Munster Under-21 Hurling Championship|Munster final]] on 28 July 2010. He ended the game with a [[Munster Under-21 Hurling Championship|Munster Championship]] medal following the 1-22 to 1-17 victory.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/sport/gaa/tipp-take-another-step-forward-126466.html|title=Tipp take another step forward|date=29 June 2010|publisher=Irish Examiner|accessdate=12 June 2019|first=Fintan|last=O'Toole}}</ref> On 11 September 2010, Barry won an [[All-Ireland Under-21 Hurling Championship|All-Ireland]] medal following Tipperary's 5-22 to 0-12 defeat of [[Galway GAA|Galway]] in the final.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.independent.ie/sport/hurling/fivestar-tipp-cruise-to-title-26680149.html|title=Five-star Tipp cruise to title|date=12 September 2010|publisher=Irish Independent|accessdate=12 June 2019|first=Damian|last=Lawlor}}</ref>

Barry was included on the Tipperary under-21 team for a second successive season in [[2011 All-Ireland Under-21 Hurling Championship|2011]]. He played his last game in the grade on 15 July 2011 when he lined out at right wing-back in a 4-19 to 1-21 defeat by Cork.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/sport/gaa/awesome-rebel-firepower-161308.html|title=Awesome Rebel firepower|date=16 July 2011|publisher=Irish Examiner|accessdate=12 June 2019|first=Fintan|last=O'Toole}}</ref> 

====Intermediate====

Barry was drafted onto the Tipperary intermediate team for the [[2012 All-Ireland Intermediate Hurling Championship#Munster Intermediate Hurling Championship|2012 Munster Championship]]. He made his first appearance for the team on 24 June 2012 when he lined out at right wing-back in a 3-18 to 2-16 defeat of Cork.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/sport/gaa/tipps-intensity-far-too-much-for-rebels-198588.html|title=Tipp’s intensity far too much for Rebels|date=25 June 2012|publisher=Irish Examiner|accessdate=12 June 2019|first=Denis|last=Hurley}}</ref> Barry was again at right wing-back when Tipperary faced Clare in the [[Munster Intermediate Hurling Championship|Munster final]] on 25 July 2012. He ended the game with a winners' medal following the 1-18 to 0-17 victory.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/sport/gaa/more-glory-for-tipp-as-clare-rue-missed-chances-202030.html|title=More glory for Tipp as Clare rue missed chances|date=26 July 2012|publisher=Irish Examiner|accessdate=12 June 2019|first=Diarmuid|last=O'Flynn}}</ref> On 1 September 2012, Barry won an [[All-Ireland Intermediate Hurling Championship|All-Ireland]] medal after lining out at right wing-back when Tipperary defeated [[Kilkenny GAA|Kilkenny]] by 3-13 to 1-17.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.independent.ie/sport/hurling/heffernan-helps-tipp-restore-some-pride-26893583.html|title=Heffernan helps Tipp restore some pride|date=2 September 2012|publisher=Irish Independent|accessdate=12 June 2019|first=|last=}}</ref>

====Senior====

Barry was added to the Tipperary senior team in advance of the [[2014 National Hurling League|2014 National League]]. He made his first appearance for the team on 23 March 2014 when he came on as a 39th-minute substitute for [[Michael Cahill]] at right wing-back in a 1-19 to 0-19 defeat of [[Dublin GAA|Dublin]].<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.independent.ie/sport/hurling/ronan-maher-makes-the-difference-in-tipp-escape-30118680.html|title=Ronan Maher makes the difference in Tipp escape|date=24 March 2014|publisher=Irish Independent|accessdate=18 June 2019|first=Martin|last=Breheny}}</ref> On 4 May 2014, Barry was at right wing-back when Tipperary suffered a 2-25 to 1-27 defeat by [[Kilkenny GAA|Kilkenny]] in the [[2014 National Hurling League|National League final]].<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.the42.ie/kilkenny-tipperary-allianz-hurling-league-final-report-1448498-May2014/|title=Kilkenny win third Allianz Hurling League in a row with last-gasp win over Tipperary|date=4 May 2014|publisher=The 42|accessdate=12 June 2019|first=Steve|last=O'Rourke}}</ref> He made his [[Munster Senior Hurling Championship|Munster Championship]] debut on 1 June 2014 when he played the full 70 minutes at right wing-back in a 2-18 to 2-16 defeat by [[Limerick GAA|Limerick]].<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.the42.ie/limerick-tipperary-munster-shc-semi-final-1496039-Jun2014/|title=Late, late show from Limerick sees them past Tipp in Munster SHC semi-final|date=1 June 2014|publisher=The 42|accessdate=12 June 2019|first=Steve|last=O'Rourke}}</ref> On 7 September 2014, Barry played in his first [[2014 All-Ireland Senior Hurling Championship Final|All-Ireland final]] against Kilkenny. He lined out full-back in the 1-28 to 3-22 draw with Kilkenny.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/sport/gaa/game-of-inches-adds-up-to-a-thriller-285397.html|title=Game of inches adds up to a thriller|date=8 September 2014|publisher=Irish Examiner|accessdate=12 June 2019|first=John|last=Fogarty}}</ref> Barry was switched to centre-back for the replay on 27 September 2014, however, he ended the game on the losing side following a 2-17 t 2-14 defeat.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.rte.ie/sport/hurling/2014/0927/648445-kilkenny-tipperary/|title=Kilkenny too strong for Tipperary in All-Ireland final replay|date=27 September 2014|publisher=RTÉ Sport|accessdate=12 June 2019|first=|last=}}</ref>

On 12 July 2015, Barry lined out at full-back in his first [[2015 Munster Senior Hurling Championship Final|Munster final]]. He ended the game with his first winners' medal following Tipperary's 0-21 to 0-16 defeat of Waterford.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-games/hurling/tipperary-claim-munster-hurling-title-with-tight-win-over-waterford-31370896.html|title=Tipperary claim Munster hurling title with tight win over Waterford|date=6 March 2012|publisher=Irish Independent|accessdate=2 January 2019|first=Seán|last=McGoldrick}}</ref> Barry ended the season by receiving an [[GAA All Stars Awards|All-Star]] nomination.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.the42.ie/2015-hurling-allstars-revealed-2363477-Oct2015/|title=Kilkenny and Galway lead the way as 2015 hurling Allstar nominations revealed|date=2 October 2015|publisher=The 42|accessdate=2 January 2019|first=Steve|last=O'Rourke}}</ref>

On 10 July 2016, Barry started the [[2016 Munster Senior Hurling Championship Final|Munster final]] against Waterford at full-back. He collected a second successive winners' medal following the 5-19 to 0-13 victory.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-games/hurling/tipp-torrents-wash-deise-hopes-away-34872402.html|title=Tipp torrents wash Deise hopes away|date=11 July 2016|publisher=Irish Independent|accessdate=2 January 2019|first=Martin|last=Breheny}}</ref> Barry was again named at full-back for the [[2016 All-Ireland Senior Hurling Championship Final|All-Ireland final]] against Kilkenny on 4 September 2016. He ended the game with an [[All-Ireland Senior Hurling Championship|All-Ireland]] medal following a 2-29 to 2-20 victory.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.the42.ie/tipperary-kilkenny-hurling-2963895-Sep2016/|title=Stunning Tipperary display clinches All-Ireland and ends Kilkenny three-in-a-row dream|date=4 September 2016|publisher=The 42|accessdate=12 June 2019|first=Fintan|last=O'Toole}}</ref> Barrett ended the season by being named in the full-back position on the All-Star team.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.the42.ie/all-star-hurling-awards-2-3062791-Nov2016/|title=7 from Tipperary and 4 from Kilkenny - the 2016 All-Star hurling team|date=4 November 2016|publisher=The 42|accessdate=12 June 2019|first=Fintan|last=O'Toole}}</ref>

On 23 April 2017, Barrett lined out at full-back when Tipperary faced Galway in the [[2017 National Hurling League#Final|National League final]]. He ended the game on the losing side following a 3-21 to 0-14 defeat.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/2017/0423/869627-galway-v-tipperary/|title=Clinical Galway leave Tipp reeling in league final|date=23 April 2017|publisher=RTÉ Sport|accessdate=12 June 2019|first=Darragh|last=Small}}</ref> 

Barry played in a second successive [[2018 National Hurling League#Final|National League final]] on 8 April 2018. Lining out at full-back he was substituted in the 60th minute after conceding 1-02 to his opponent [[Walter Walsh (hurler)|Walter Walsh]]. Tipperary eventually lost the game to Kilkenny by 2-23 to 2-17.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-games/hurling/kilkenny-whirlwind-blows-tipperary-away-as-brian-cody-claims-ninth-league-title-36786246.html|title=Kilkenny whirlwind blows Tipperary away as Brian Cody claims ninth league title|date=8 April 2018|publisher=Irish Independent|accessdate=12 June 2019|first=Seán|last=McGoldrick}}</ref>

On 30 June 2019, Barry lined out at full-back in his third [[2019 Munster Senior Hurling Championship Final|Munster final]] when Tipperary faced Limerick. He was substituted by [[Barry Heffernan]] in the 62nd minute and ended the game on the losing side after a 2-26 to 2-14 defeat.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.the42.ie/limerick-tipperary-munster-hurling-4703771-Jun2019/|title=More glory for Limerick as they lift Munster crown with 12-point win over Tipperary|date=30 June 2019|publisher=The 42|accessdate=1 July 2019|first=Fintan|last=O'Toole}}</ref>

